Granted, domains don't come and go overnight, but the length of your
message should indicate the tedium of setting up rules for any new
domain that might come along.  My method provides a consistent scheme
for any domain configuration, and doesn't allow the possibility of a
programmer screwing up and routing your mail to oshkosh because of a
defaulting error.  The penalty is having to add several dots to a host
name when crossing a domain boundary, which can avoided for the most
common hosts by ideas such as an alias file.  Most importantly, my
scheme involves zero unnecessary resolver calls, which will help the
domain servers and keep network traffic down.

-Robert
